│ stop({"edit_points": [[418, 418, "llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue: The problem occurs in the correlated-propagation pass when processing │
│ a switch instruction with a PHI node condition that has values -1 (255 as unsigned) and 0. The pass incorrectly determines that the default destination is unreachable and replaces it with an unreachable     │
│ block, causing undefined behavior. The source can reach the exit block (when %phi = -1), but the transformed code makes this path unreachable.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the pass        │
│ removes all switch cases and creates a 'default.unreachable' block with an unreachable instruction. The key issue is in the logic that determines if the default destination is unreachable based on the       │
│ constant range analysis.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The bug is in line 418 of CorrelatedValuePropagation.cpp. The code checks if `!CR.isSizeLargerThan(ReachableCaseCount)` to determine if the default        │
│ destination is unreachable. However, the ConstantRange for the PHI node is [255, 2) which represents the range {255, 0, 1} (wrapping range). This range has size 3, and ReachableCaseCount is also 3 (cases 0, │
│ 1, 2 are considered reachable). The condition `!CR.isSizeLargerThan(3)` evaluates to true because CR.size() == 3, leading the pass to incorrectly conclude that all possible values are covered by the cases.  │
│ However, the actual value -1 (255) is not covered by any case (cases are 0, 1, 2), so the default destination should remain reachable.\n\nThe issue is that the pass assumes that if the constant range size   │
│ equals the number of reachable cases, then all values in the range are covered by the cases. This is incorrect for wrapping ranges or when the cases don't actually cover all values in the range.\n\n4.       │
│ Proposed Edit Point(s): The fix is to change the condition from checking if the range size is not larger than the reachable case count to actually verifying that all values in the constant range are covered │
│ by the switch cases. However, since this requires more complex logic, a simpler and safer fix is to disable this optimization when dealing with wrapping ranges, as they are more complex to analyze           │
│ correctly.\n\n5. Conclusion: By modifying the condition to only apply the default destination unreachable optimization when the constant range is non-wrapping, we prevent the incorrect transformation that   │
│ leads to undefined behavior. This ensures that cases like the reproducer, where a wrapping range contains values not covered by any switch case, will not incorrectly eliminate the default destination."})    │
